"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Romans chapters 11–14
Christological trajectory commentary for each verse.
Five directness levels: "A direct revelation:", "A revelation of God:", "A type:", "A shadow:", "A fulfillment:"
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-romans-11-14.py
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ROMANS = {
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>A fulfillment: Paul\'s own existence as a believing Israelite — a Benjaminite, a member of the tribe that remained with Judah and from which Israel\'s first king came — is the living fulfillment of the OT remnant promise. The question "has God rejected his people?" is answered not by a logical argument alone but by a person: Paul himself is the firstfruits of the preserved remnant in his generation. His conversion on the Damascus road is thus not merely a personal salvation event but a sign of God\'s continuing faithfulness to Israel — an epistle written in flesh.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "God has not rejected his people whom he foreknew." The divine foreknowing (<em>proegnō</em>) of Israel expresses the covenantal love that precedes and grounds the entire history of election. God\'s non-rejection of Israel is not a concession to Israel\'s merit but an expression of who God is: the faithful covenant-keeper who does not abandon what he has begun. The character of God disclosed in Israel\'s election — steadfast love, covenant faithfulness, persistence in redemptive purpose despite human failure — is the same character disclosed fully in the cross and resurrection of Jesus Christ.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A type: Elijah\'s complaint that he alone remains — "I am the only one left, and they are trying to kill me" (1 Kgs 19:10) — is the type of the prophet who does not know the extent of God\'s preserved people. Elijah\'s experience prefigures the church\'s experience of feeling alone in a hostile world while God maintains a hidden remnant. The type is not Christ directly but the prophetic pattern of isolation-and-divine-assurance that the Messiah himself enacted: Jesus in Gethsemane, abandoned by his disciples, sustained by the Father\'s purpose.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A shadow: The 7,000 who had not bowed the knee to Baal are the shadow of the new covenant community — the people defined not by public religious conformity but by heart-allegiance to the true God. Their hiddenness in Elijah\'s time anticipates the hiddenness of the faithful community in every age: the true people of God are not always visible in the social-religious landscape. Christ himself was the hidden one, unrecognized by the religious establishment, whose identity was revealed only to those whose eyes were opened.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "So too at the present time there is a remnant chosen by grace." The pattern of the grace-remnant discloses the character of divine election: God preserves a people not through their collective performance but through sovereign grace. This is not a secondary feature of the divine character but its central expression — the God who is "gracious and compassionate, slow to anger and abounding in steadfast love" (Exod 34:6-7) reveals this character most clearly in preserving the undeserving. Christ himself is the ultimate expression of this grace: the one through whom the grace-remnant is constituted.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation: "But if it is by grace, it is no longer on the basis of works; otherwise grace would no longer be grace." This is the clearest possible statement of the logic of the gospel: grace and works are mutually exclusive as grounds of divine favor, not because works are bad but because grace by definition is unearned. Christ\'s work revealed this logic definitively: if righteousness were achievable through works, the cross was unnecessary. The cross reveals that no human performance could constitute the basis of divine acceptance — only grace, actualized in the sacrifice of Christ, could accomplish what law could not.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "What Israel was seeking, it did not obtain; the elect obtained it, but the rest were hardened." The divine hardening — the judicial withdrawal of spiritual perception from those who persistently rejected the light — reveals the holiness of God who does not coerce response. God is not merely the generous offerer of grace but the holy Judge whose patience has limits. The hardening serves redemptive purposes within the larger plan (vv11-15), but it is real judicial action. Christ\'s crucifixion was simultaneously the supreme display of divine love and the supreme act of human hardening — the rejection of the very source of light.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A fulfillment: The "spirit of stupor" from Deut 29:4 and Isa 29:10 — applied by Paul to Israel\'s current inability to see — is fulfilled in the pattern Jesus himself described: the parables were given so that "seeing they may not see, and hearing they may not understand" (Luke 8:10, citing Isa 6:9-10). The judicial hardening that Israel experienced in failing to recognize their Messiah was itself the fulfillment of the prophetic pattern — not an accident but an enacted prophecy. The one who was rejected became the test-stone: the same Christ who was the light was the occasion of the hardening of those who refused him.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A type: The table of blessing becoming a snare (Ps 69:22-23, applied by Paul to Israel\'s rejection of the Messiah) enacts the typological reversal that the gospel brings at every level. The table prepared in the wilderness (the manna), the table of the Levitical feasts, the table of the Passover — all were types of the messianic banquet. Israel\'s rejection of Jesus at the Last Supper table, where the bread and cup were redefined as his body and blood, is the moment when the table of blessing becomes the table of judgment for those who refuse to receive him.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A shadow: The bent back and blinded eyes of Ps 69:23 — describing the curse that falls on those who reject the righteous sufferer — are the shadow of the blindness that afflicts those who will not see the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ (2 Cor 4:4-6). The curse of physical incapacitation in the Psalm becomes in Paul the spiritual incapacitation of those whose minds the god of this age has blinded. The full light of Christ shines, but those under judicial hardening cannot receive it — not because the light is dim but because their eyes are sealed.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: Israel\'s stumbling becoming the occasion of Gentile salvation discloses the providential wisdom of God who turns human rejection into redemptive opportunity. This is the pattern of the cross writ large in salvation history: the rejection of the Messiah by Israel became the occasion of the gospel\'s proclamation to all nations (Acts 13:46-47; 18:6). God\'s ability to make human sin and failure serve redemptive purposes — without either causing the sin or being frustrated by it — reveals a dimension of divine wisdom that the angels long to look into (1 Pet 1:12).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "If their failure means riches for the world... how much more will their full inclusion mean!" The divine logic of overflowing grace — that partial failure produces great riches for many — discloses the superabundant character of divine generosity. The cross operates by the same logic: one death produces life for the many (5:15-21); one rejection produces reception for the nations. The eschatological expectation of Israel\'s "fullness" bringing even greater riches to the world points toward the consummation when God\'s purposes, frustrated at no point by human unbelief, achieve their final universal expression.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: Paul\'s ministry as apostle to the Gentiles, which is simultaneously a ministry toward Israel\'s redemption, reveals the divine strategy of indirect approach — reaching the "near" through the "far." God\'s ways are not our ways: where we might expect direct appeal to produce direct response, God works through the unlikely path of Gentile blessing to provoke Israel\'s recognition of what they have passed by. This wisdom is the wisdom of the cross: the path to life runs through death, the path to Israel\'s salvation runs through Gentile blessing.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: The love that motivates Paul\'s ministry — his desire to "save some of them" — mirrors the divine desire for universal salvation (1 Tim 2:4; 2 Pet 3:9). Paul\'s anguish for Israel (9:3) and his hope for their salvation (10:1; 11:14) are participations in the divine pathos — the grief of the shepherd for the lost sheep, the longing of the father for the returning son. Paul\'s ministry embodies the missionary character of God who seeks what is lost not by imposing but by invitation.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A type: "Their rejection is the reconciliation of the world; what will their acceptance be but life from the dead?" The pattern invoked is Ezekiel\'s valley of dry bones (Ezek 37): Israel\'s national death and resurrection as the sign of cosmic renewal. Paul identifies Israel\'s acceptance in the eschatological future as the moment when the new creation\'s full arrival breaks into history — "life from the dead" understood as the general resurrection itself. The type-to-fulfillment movement is: Israel\'s restoration (Ezekiel\'s promise) → the resurrection of the dead (Paul\'s eschatological hope) → the new creation (the final fulfillment of God\'s purposes in Christ).</p>',
    "16": '<p>A type: The firstfruits offering that consecrates the entire lump (Num 15:18-21) is fulfilled in Christ as the firstfruits of the resurrection (1 Cor 15:20-23). If Christ the firstfruits is holy (consecrated, set apart for God, raised from the dead), then those who belong to him — the "whole batch" — share that consecration and that resurrection. Paul\'s application to the patriarchs as firstfruits of Israel functions by the same logic: if Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob are holy (chosen by God), Israel participates in that holiness. But the ultimate firstfruits who consecrates all others is Christ himself.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A shadow: The olive tree — the cultivated tree into which wild branches are grafted — is the shadow of the new covenant people constituted around Christ. The natural olive tree with its deep root in the Abrahamic covenant is the shadow of the covenant-people; Christ is the root himself (as v18 implies: "it is not you who supports the root, but the root supports you"). The grafting of wild Gentile branches into the cultivated olive tree is the shadow made visible in the Gentile mission: Gentiles are incorporated into Israel\'s covenant story through union with Christ, the olive root.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct revelation: "It is not you who supports the root, but the root supports you." The root of the olive tree — the Abrahamic covenant, the patriarchal blessing — supports the Gentile branches, not vice versa. In Paul\'s Christological reading, Christ is the root (Col 1:17: "in him all things hold together"; John 15:1: "I am the true vine"): the Gentile church does not create or sustain the covenant but is sustained by Christ, who is the fulfillment and embodiment of the Abrahamic promise. Boasting against the natural branches (Israel) is therefore a boasting against the root that supports the boaster.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: The logic that unbelieving branches were broken off to make room for Gentile branches — stated by the hypothetical Gentile objector — is not entirely wrong but profoundly misunderstands the asymmetry of grace. God\'s grafting in of Gentiles was not contingent on Israel\'s failure; it was always the divine intention (Isa 2:2-4; 49:6; 60:1-3). Israel\'s failure did not cause the Gentile mission; the Gentile mission was always part of the purpose that Israel\'s election was designed to serve. Misreading divine sovereignty to mean "I am the privileged replacement" is the error the Gentile church has historically been most prone to make.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "Do not be proud but be afraid" — the healthy fear of the holy God who does not show favoritism is itself a disclosure of divine character. The God who broke off natural branches for unbelief is the same God who will break off grafted branches for arrogance and unbelief. Divine mercy does not eliminate divine holiness; divine election does not eliminate the condition of faith. The warning reveals the moral seriousness of the God who is both "kind and stern" (v22) — attributes that find their ultimate expression in the cross, where both divine love and divine justice are simultaneously displayed.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "If God did not spare the natural branches, he will not spare you either." The argument from Israel\'s history to the Gentile church\'s present is grounded in the consistency of God\'s character. The God who maintains covenant standards does not vary them based on ethnic privilege or group membership. The same holiness that held natural Israel accountable will hold grafted Gentile branches accountable. This moral consistency — God treating all by the same standard — is itself good news: the same God who does not play favorites also does not abandon his mercy toward any who turn to him in faith.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: "Consider the kindness and sternness of God." The two-attribute revelation of God — simultaneously kind (<em>chrēstotēs</em>) and stern (<em>apotomia</em>) — is one of the most precise descriptions of the divine character in Paul. Both attributes are disclosed fully in the cross: God\'s sternness is displayed in the reality of judgment on sin (the cross was not a gentle resolution but a violent atonement); God\'s kindness is displayed in the giving of his Son to bear that judgment. The cross does not resolve the tension between kindness and sternness by eliminating one of them; it demonstrates that both are simultaneously true of the God who is love.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "If they do not persist in unbelief, they will be grafted in, for God is able to graft them in again." The divine ability (<em>dynatos</em>) to restore what has been broken off is the revelation of God\'s sovereign mercy — the same ability Paul attributed to God in 4:21 (Abraham\'s faith in God\'s ability to do what he promised). The eschatological hope for Israel is not optimistic humanism about human potential for repentance but theological confidence in God\'s power to accomplish the impossible. The God who raised Jesus from the dead is certainly able to graft broken branches back into the living olive tree.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: The argument from "against nature" (grafting wild olive into cultivated) to "according to nature" (grafting natural branches back in) reveals divine consistency: what seems like an unprecedented act (Gentile inclusion) is actually preparation for the more natural act (Israel\'s restoration). God\'s purposes have an internal logic — what he does with the nations has always been aimed at what he will do with Israel. The olive tree metaphor discloses a divine master-plan in which both Israel and the nations have their proper place, not one replacing the other but both belonging to the cultivated tree rooted in Christ.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "I do not want you to be ignorant of this mystery, brothers and sisters." The disclosure of the eschatological mystery — Israel\'s partial hardening until the fullness of the Gentiles, followed by all Israel\'s salvation — is direct divine revelation through the apostle. This is not Paul\'s theological inference alone but apostolic <em>mysterion</em> — the revealed secret of the divine plan that was previously hidden but has now been disclosed (cf. Eph 3:3-6; Col 1:26-27). The content of the mystery frames all of chs9-11: God\'s purpose for Israel and the nations has not failed; it is being accomplished according to a hidden plan now revealed in Christ and his apostle.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A fulfillment: "All Israel will be saved, as it is written: The deliverer will come from Zion; he will turn godlessness away from Jacob." The citation of Isa 59:20-21 identifies the deliverer who will save all Israel as the risen and exalted Christ, who will come from the heavenly Zion at the parousia. Paul\'s modification of Isaiah ("from Zion" instead of the Hebrew "to Zion") reflects a Christological reading: the deliverer is not merely an earthly king returning to Jerusalem but the exalted Lord coming from the heavenly city (cf. Heb 12:22-24; Rev 21:2). The eschatological salvation of all Israel is grounded in Christ\'s return.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A fulfillment: "And this will be my covenant with them when I take away their sins" (citing Isa 59:21 and Jer 31:33-34). The new covenant promise of Jer 31 — "I will forgive their wickedness and remember their sins no more" — reaches its fulfillment first at the cross (the new covenant in Christ\'s blood, Luke 22:20; Heb 8:8-12) and will reach its final fulfillment in Israel\'s eschatological restoration. The sin-forgiveness that the new covenant promises is the same forgiveness that Christ\'s death accomplished (3:25-26); Israel\'s future salvation will be the application of the same gospel to the same people who rejected it in the first coming.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: "As far as election is concerned, they are loved on account of the patriarchs; for God\'s gifts and his call are irrevocable." The irrevocability of the divine gifts discloses the divine faithfulness (<em>emet</em> = truth/faithfulness) that is one of the foundational attributes of the God of Israel. The God who loves Israel "on account of the patriarchs" is the God who keeps covenant promises across generations — the God who remembers his covenant with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob (Exod 2:24; Lev 26:42). This faithfulness is the same faithfulness that brought Christ into the world to fulfill the promises made to the fathers (15:8).</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: "For God\'s gifts and his call are irrevocable." This principle of divine irrevocability — that what God has given cannot be taken back, and what God has called cannot be uncalled — is the theological foundation for the eschatological hope for Israel. It is also the foundation for every believer\'s security (8:38-39: nothing can separate us from the love of God). The same divine character that makes God\'s covenant with Israel irrevocable makes his covenant with every believer in Christ irrevocable: the same faithfulness operates at both levels.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: The symmetrical mercy-structure of vv30-31 — Gentiles formerly disobedient, now received mercy through Israel\'s disobedience; Israel currently disobedient, will receive mercy through the mercy shown to Gentiles — reveals a divine economy of grace that works through apparent failure to accomplish actual redemption. This is the cross-logic operating at the macroscopic level of salvation history: failure becomes the occasion of mercy, rejection becomes the door of opportunity, apparent defeat becomes actual triumph. God is the master of redemptive reversal.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: Israel\'s current disobedience being the occasion of their future mercy reveals the eschatological patience of God. The God who allows disobedience for the purpose of demonstrating mercy is not passive or powerless but is the God who sees the end from the beginning and works all things according to the counsel of his will (Eph 1:11). The "now" of available mercy in Paul\'s gospel does not eliminate the future mercy for Israel; it inaugurates it. The same Christ who brought mercy to the Gentiles will bring mercy to all Israel at his return.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A direct revelation: "God has bound all under disobedience so that he may have mercy on all." This is one of Paul\'s most provocative theological statements — that the universal captivity to disobedience is itself part of the divine design, so that mercy rather than merit is the universal mode of divine-human relationship. The cross makes this universal structure explicit: if all were bound under disobedience and Christ bore the judgment for all, then mercy is available to all on the same terms. The radical equality of human need and divine provision in Christ is the practical expression of this theological principle.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "Oh the depth of the riches of the wisdom and knowledge of God!" The doxology converts the theological argument into worship — the only appropriate response to the revelation of God\'s ways in Christ. The incomprehensibility of divine wisdom disclosed in the gospel (1 Cor 1:18-25: "the foolishness of the cross is the wisdom of God") prevents the theologian from domesticating what has been revealed. The "depth" of divine wisdom is not merely beyond human calculation but is the infinite abyss of a personal God whose ways are genuinely other than ours.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "Who has known the mind of the Lord? Or who has been his counselor?" The citation of Isa 40:13 — from the section that describes the incomparable God who created all things — is applied to the specific wisdom of God\'s plan for Israel and the nations. The rhetorical questions function as doxology: no human advisor has contributed to God\'s plan; no human mind has fathomed it. The wisdom revealed in the Christ-event exceeds what any prophet, scribe, or philosopher had imagined. Yet it has been disclosed — in the crucified and risen Messiah who is the wisdom of God (1 Cor 1:24).</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "Who has first given to God, that God should repay them?" The citation of Job 41:11 — from God\'s speech from the whirlwind establishing divine sovereignty over creation — applies to the economy of salvation. No human being has established a prior claim on God; no creature has gifted the Creator. This means salvation is entirely gift and grace, not reciprocal exchange. The cross is the ultimate demonstration of this: God did not act to repay a prior human gift but acted first, in love, while we were still sinners (5:8). All of salvation flows from divine initiative, not human prior action.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A direct revelation: "For from him and through him and to him are all things. To him be the glory forever, amen." The triadic cosmological formula applied to God — source (<em>ex autou</em>), sustainer (<em>di\' autou</em>), goal (<em>eis auton</em>) of all things — is in Colossians 1:16 applied to Christ: "all things were created through him and for him." The echo is not accidental: the God who is "from him and through him and to him" in Romans 11 is the same God fully disclosed in Christ, through whom and for whom all creation exists. The doxology that closes chs9-11 is ultimately a doxology to the triune God whose purposes have been unveiled in the gospel.</p>'
  },
  "12": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "Present your bodies as a living sacrifice, holy and pleasing to God — this is your true and proper worship." The transformation of sacrifice from dead animal to living person is the direct revelation of the new covenant\'s nature. The OT sacrificial system — in which the animal was killed and the worshiper watched — is replaced by the new covenant in which the worshiper becomes the offering. Christ\'s own sacrifice — the living, willing, obedient offering of himself to the Father (Heb 10:5-10; Eph 5:2) — is the pattern for this new worship. The believer\'s "reasonable worship" is participation in Christ\'s own self-offering to the Father.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "Be transformed by the renewing of your mind." The transformation (<em>metamorphōsis</em>) Paul calls for is the human side of the divine act of conforming believers to Christ\'s image (8:29: "to be conformed to the image of his Son"). The renewal of the mind is the Spirit\'s work (Eph 4:23: "be made new in the attitude of your minds") that enables the discernment of God\'s will — a discernment that Christ himself perfectly embodied. The "renewed mind" is the mind that sees as God sees, evaluates as God evaluates — the mind of Christ (1 Cor 2:16) increasingly operational in the believer.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: The call to "sober judgment" according to the "measure of faith" distributed by God reveals the divine wisdom in distributing gifts differentially for the community\'s benefit. The God who gives different measures of faith and different charismata to different members is the same God whose own being is the perfect unity of differentiated relationships — Father, Son, and Spirit each distinct yet perfectly one. The community that lives by the logic of differentiated gifts functioning for unified purpose is an image of the Trinitarian God from whom all gifts come.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A shadow: The human body with its many members of different function is the shadow of the church as Christ\'s body. Paul\'s body-metaphor points to its fulfillment in the incarnation: the divine Logos who became embodied in flesh (John 1:14) is now present in the world through his body the church (Col 1:24; Eph 1:22-23). The physical body — with its unified coordination of eyes, hands, feet, and all members — is the shadow; the church as Christ\'s embodied presence in the world is the fulfillment. What the body does for the individual person, the church-body does for Christ in the world.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: "So in Christ we, though many, form one body, and each member belongs to all the others." The Christological grounding of community unity — "in Christ" (<em>en Christō</em>) as the sphere of mutual belonging — is the revelation that distinguishes Christian community from all merely social or philosophical unities. The "one body in Christ" is constituted by participation in Christ, not by natural affinity or social contract. The mutual belonging ("each member belongs to all the others") reflects the self-giving love of Christ — the one who gave himself for others becomes the model and ground of mutual belonging.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: The diversity of spiritual gifts "according to the grace given to us" reveals the generosity of God who supplies what each member and the whole community needs. The <em>charismata</em> (grace-gifts) distributed by the Spirit (1 Cor 12:4-11) are expressions of the same divine grace that justified the believer; the gifts are not earned but received, not achievements but endowments. Christ, who received the Spirit without measure (John 3:34), is the source from whom the measured gifts overflow to the members of his body.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A shadow: The temple service (<em>diakonia</em>) performed by the Levitical priests and servers is the shadow of the ministry that the whole community now performs as a royal priesthood (1 Pet 2:9). The professional ministries of the OT temple system — teaching (the scribes and priests), serving (the Levites), leading (the elders and kings) — are now distributed across the entire community as each member exercises their gift. The democratization of ministry is the fulfillment of Moses\'s wish: "Would that all the LORD\'s people were prophets" (Num 11:29), actualized through the Spirit poured out on all flesh (Acts 2:17-18).</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: The gifts of giving "with singleness" (<em>en haplotēti</em>), leading "with diligence" (<em>en spoudē</em>), and showing mercy "with cheerfulness" (<em>en hilarotēti</em>) reflect the character of the God who gives himself without calculation, who accomplishes his purposes without delay, and who shows mercy with delight rather than reluctance (Ps 147:11; Zeph 3:17: "he will rejoice over you with gladness"). The community\'s life of service mirrors the divine character disclosed in Christ, who gave himself completely, acted decisively, and received sinners with joy (Luke 15:1-2).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "Love must be sincere" (<em>hē agapē anypokritos</em>) — the love that is without mask or performance — reveals the character of the divine love that sent Christ. The love of God in Christ was not calculating or performative; it was the genuine self-giving that went to the cross not for advantage but for the beloved. The command "hate what is evil; cling to what is good" reflects the holiness that always accompanies genuine love: the God who is love (1 John 4:16) is also the God who hates evil (Ps 5:5; Prov 6:16-19). Divine love and divine holiness are not in tension but are two expressions of the one character disclosed in Christ.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: Devoted brotherly love and outdo-one-another-in-honor are the community expressions of the divine love that "does not seek its own" (1 Cor 13:5). Christ\'s own pattern — "do nothing out of selfish ambition or vain conceit, but in humility consider others better than yourselves" (Phil 2:3) — is the model for the community\'s mutual honor. The one who "did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped but emptied himself" (Phil 2:6-7) is both the pattern and the power for the honor-giving community.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: The Spirit-fervor that the community is to maintain reflects the Spirit\'s own character — the divine fire that is neither passive nor exhausted. The Pentecost fire (Acts 2:3) was not a temporary ignition but the ongoing empowerment of the church\'s mission. Serving the Lord with Spirit-fervor is participation in the life of the Spirit himself, who intercedes with "unutterable groanings" (8:26) and whose fruit includes joy and faithfulness (Gal 5:22-23). The "not lagging in zeal" is the human expression of the inexhaustible divine energy at work in the community.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A shadow: The patient endurance and persistent prayer of the community in tribulation are the shadow of the endurance and prayer of Christ himself. Jesus endured the cross "for the joy set before him" (Heb 12:2) — sustaining himself through hope of the resurrection; he "prayed constantly" and "offered up prayers and petitions with fervent cries and tears" (Heb 5:7). The community\'s triad of hope-rejoicing, tribulation-endurance, and persistent prayer is the participation of Christ\'s body in the same pattern of life that Christ himself embodied in his incarnate existence.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: The hospitality that the community extends to strangers (<em>philoxenia</em>) reflects the divine hospitality that received strangers into the covenant: "you were foreigners and strangers... no longer foreigners but fellow citizens with God\'s people" (Eph 2:12, 19). Christ himself was the divine stranger who entered the world he created: "he came to what was his own, and his own people did not receive him. But to all who did receive him, he gave the right to become children of God" (John 1:11-12). The community that practices radical hospitality enacts the divine welcome that it has itself received in Christ.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct revelation: "Bless those who persecute you; bless and do not curse." This is the direct application of Christ\'s cross-ethic to the community\'s social practice. Jesus himself prayed from the cross: "Father, forgive them, for they do not know what they are doing" (Luke 23:34). Stephen, the first martyr, prayed the same prayer as stones struck him (Acts 7:60). The enemy-blessing ethic is not merely a new moral standard but a participation in the cross itself: the community that blesses persecutors enacts what Christ enacted, extends what Christ extended, and reveals to the world the God who blesses the undeserving.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "Rejoice with those who rejoice; mourn with those who mourn." The empathetic solidarity that Paul commands reflects the divine pathos — God\'s genuine engagement with human joy and sorrow. "In all their distress he too was distressed" (Isa 63:9); God neither stood aloof from human suffering nor was overwhelmed by it but entered it. Christ\'s weeping at Lazarus\'s tomb (John 11:35) and his rejoicing at the disciples\' return (Luke 10:21) are the incarnate expressions of this empathetic character. The community that genuinely shares in one another\'s emotional life images the God who genuinely shares in ours.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: The call to associate with the lowly — to not be proud but to go where the humble are — reflects the divine condescension that is the character of God in Christ. "Though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor" (2 Cor 8:9); the one who was Lord of all "took the very nature of a servant" (Phil 2:7). The community that refuses to be wise in its own estimation and instead descends to associate with the lowly is following the downward path that God himself took in the Incarnation. The wisdom that is not self-referential is the wisdom of the cross.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "Do not repay anyone evil for evil." The non-retaliatory character of the community\'s response to harm reflects the divine patience (<em>anochē</em>, 2:4) that withholds judgment to make space for repentance. God does not immediately respond to evil with evil; if he did, no one would survive (Ps 130:3). Christ\'s cross is the supreme expression of divine non-retaliation: the Son of God received evil and returned good, absorbed judgment and released forgiveness, bore the world\'s hostility and proclaimed peace. The community\'s non-retaliation is participation in the cross-logic of God.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "As far as it depends on you, live at peace with all." The qualification "as far as it depends on you" is both realistic and revelatory: it acknowledges that peace requires two parties while insisting that the community controls only its own side. God himself is the supreme peace-seeker who does what is possible on his side — sending his Son, offering reconciliation, waiting patiently — without coercing the human response. The community that lives peaceably "as far as it depends on them" participates in the divine seeking of shalom that Paul has described throughout the letter.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "Do not take revenge, my dear friends, but leave room for God\'s wrath." The entrusting of vengeance to God is not an abdication of justice but a recognition that justice belongs to God\'s domain. The cross demonstrates that God has not ignored evil: the full weight of divine judgment fell on the crucified Son. God\'s wrath is real and will be enacted (Rev 6:16-17; 2 Thess 1:7-9); the community\'s refusal to enact its own revenge is trust that God\'s justice will be perfectly accomplished. The God of the cross is also the God of the final judgment — the same character expressing itself in both love and justice.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A shadow: The "coals of fire" placed on the enemy\'s head through acts of generosity is the shadow of the gospel itself — the surprising, shame-inducing power of grace to melt hostility. The Proverbs principle (Prov 25:21-22) points toward the cross: the supreme act of enemy-love, in which Christ died for his enemies (5:10), is the fire that melts the hardness of the human heart. The community that practices the cross-ethic of feeding enemies participates in the same gospel logic that brought enemies into reconciliation with God.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "Do not be overcome by evil, but overcome evil with good." This principle is not merely an ethical maxim but a description of the gospel\'s operative logic. The world overcomes evil with greater evil — more force, more retaliation, more control. The gospel overcomes evil with good — with love for enemies, blessing for persecutors, forgiveness for the guilty. Christ\'s resurrection was the supreme "overcoming evil with good": death overcame by life, hatred overcome by love, the rejection of the cross overcome by the acceptance of resurrection. The community that overcomes evil with good continues this victory in the world.</p>'
  },
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>A shadow: The governing authorities that Paul describes as "God\'s servants" for the ordering of human society are the shadow of the ultimate divine ordering — the kingdom of God in which justice, peace, and righteousness are perfectly administered by the righteous Judge. Every human government, even imperfect and pagan, is a shadow of the divine government that is coming. Their function of rewarding good and punishing evil (vv3-4) is a partial expression of the divine justice that will be fully enacted at the final judgment. Christ is the Lord to whom all governing authorities are ultimately accountable (Rev 1:5: "the ruler of the kings of the earth").</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: Resistance to legitimate authority is resistance to "what God has instituted" (<em>tē tou theou diatagē</em>) — the divine ordering that governance represents. The God who established human governing structures is the same God who governs all things through his sovereign wisdom. The theological grounding of civic authority in divine appointment does not absolutize the state but places it within the framework of divine accountability: governing authorities are servants, not lords; they derive authority from God and are answerable to God for how they exercise it.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A shadow: The ruler who holds no terror for those who do good is the shadow of the perfect Judge who will hold no condemnation for those in Christ (8:1). Human governing authorities — even in their imperfect form — embody a partial truth: righteousness and goodness should produce approval rather than fear; wrongdoing should produce judgment. The eschatological ruler who perfectly rewards the righteous and punishes the wicked is Christ himself, before whose judgment seat all will appear (14:10; 2 Cor 5:10). The present governing authority is a shadow pointing to that ultimate tribunal.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A shadow: The government official as "God\'s servant" who "bears the sword" as an "agent of wrath" against wrongdoers is the shadow of the divine justice that Christ will enact at the parousia. In the present age, God\'s wrath against evil is enacted through human institutions (governments, courts, military forces) that preserve some semblance of order. At the end of the age, Christ himself will execute the divine judgment directly (Rev 19:11-16: "he treads the winepress of the fury of the wrath of God Almighty"). The governmental sword is a pale, imperfect shadow of the sword of divine judgment.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: The dual motivation for submission — fear of punishment and conscience — reveals the two dimensions of the divine character: holiness (which produces appropriate fear) and goodness (which appeals to conscience and moral understanding). The God who commands submission to governing authorities is the same God who gives conscience the capacity to recognize right from wrong. Submission motivated by conscience is more than external compliance; it is an acknowledgment that the divine ordering of human society is genuinely good, even in its imperfect human expression.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A shadow: The taxes and revenues paid to the governing authorities who are "God\'s servants" are the shadow of the tribute that all creation owes to the divine sovereign. Jesus\'s "render to Caesar what is Caesar\'s and to God what is God\'s" (Mark 12:17) maintains the distinction: Caesar\'s coin bears Caesar\'s image; the human being bears God\'s image (Gen 1:26-27). The tribute owed to Caesar is real but derivative; the ultimate tribute — worship, obedience, love — is owed to God alone. Paying earthly taxes is the shadow of the great rendering of the whole self to God called for in 12:1.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "Give to everyone what you owe them: taxes, revenue, respect, honor" — the principle of giving each party their due is the divine justice principle applied to civic life. The God who is perfectly just gives each according to their due at the final judgment; human society works by the partial application of this principle through governing structures. Christ himself embodied this justice: he "rendered to God" perfect obedience and love; he honored governing authority (paying the temple tax, submitting to Pilate\'s jurisdiction) while reserving ultimate allegiance for the Father.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct revelation: "Let no debt remain outstanding, except the continuing debt to love one another." The love-debt that never gets paid off is the direct revelation of the character of the new covenant community: love as the permanent, inexhaustible obligation of those who have received inexhaustible love. Christ\'s love for his people is the permanent, never-completed gift: "having loved his own who were in the world, he loved them to the end" (John 13:1). The community\'s love for one another is the response to and extension of that inexhaustible love — a debt that grows as it is paid, not diminishes.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A fulfillment: The commandments of the Decalogue — do not commit adultery, murder, steal, covet — summarized in Leviticus 19:18 ("love your neighbor as yourself") reach their fulfillment in Christ\'s new commandment: "Love one another as I have loved you" (John 13:34-35; 15:12). The OT summary is <em>kata</em> (according to) the standard of self-love; Christ\'s summary is <em>kata</em> (according to) the standard of his own self-giving love — a higher standard that fulfills the OT command while transcending it. The law finds its fullness not in more rules but in the person of Christ whose love is the living fulfillment of all commandments.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct revelation: "Love is the fulfillment of the law." Christ himself is the fulfillment of the law (10:4) and the embodiment of love (1 John 4:10: "this is love: not that we loved God, but that he loved us and sent his Son as an atoning sacrifice"). If love is the fulfillment of the law, and Christ is love incarnate, then Christ is the fulfillment of the law by being love — the law\'s deepest intention made concrete in a person. The community that loves fulfills the law not by obeying a code but by participating in the character of Christ whose love was the law\'s content all along.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct revelation: "Our salvation is nearer now than when we first believed." The nearness of eschatological salvation is a direct revelation of the temporal structure of the new covenant: the Christ-event inaugurated the end-time, and every moment that passes brings the consummation closer. The "hour to wake from sleep" is not merely a moral awakening but an eschatological one: the new creation has already begun in the resurrection of Christ, and the community is called to live as citizens of the arriving kingdom rather than as permanent residents of the present age that is "nearly over" (<em>prokopsen hē nyx</em>).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct revelation: "The night is nearly over; the day is almost here." The day/night cosmological language is Christological: Christ is the "sun of righteousness" who rises with healing in his wings (Mal 4:2), the "dayspring from on high" who has come to give light to those in darkness (Luke 1:78), the "light of the world" (John 8:12) whose resurrection is the breaking of the new creation dawn. The community\'s "putting on the armor of light" is participation in the inaugurated new day — living as those who already belong to the day, even while the night of the present age still covers the world.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: The behaviors to be abandoned — reveling, drunkenness, sexual immorality, sensuality, strife, jealousy — are precisely the behaviors that express the "flesh" orientation described in ch8. They are the deeds of the night, the works of the old age that is passing away. The God who calls his community out of these behaviors is the God who has called them into the light of his new creation in Christ — not merely demanding behavioral change but providing the ontological basis for it: they are already "sons of light" (1 Thess 5:5) who are called to live according to their new nature.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct revelation: "Clothe yourself with the Lord Jesus Christ." The baptismal imagery of putting on Christ (Gal 3:27) is the direct revelation of what union with Christ means for daily life: not merely believing in Christ but wearing Christ — allowing his character, priorities, and manner of life to be the "clothes" in which one moves through the world. "Making no provision for the flesh" is the negative correlate: not planning ahead for the indulgence of the old life. Christ himself, who "went about doing good" (Acts 10:38) and "did not please himself" (15:3), is the model of what it means to "wear" the character of the new humanity.</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: The welcome that the "strong" are to extend to the "weak in faith" reflects the divine welcome that Christ extended to sinners, tax collectors, and the excluded: "Accept one another, then, just as Christ has accepted you, in order to bring praise to God" (15:7). God\'s welcome in Christ is the ground and model of the community\'s welcome of one another — not welcome based on agreement on every point but welcome based on the common ground of belonging to Christ. The diversity of practice within the community (one eats, one abstains) is covered by the unity of belonging (all belong to the same Lord).</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: The difference between the one who eats everything and the one who eats only vegetables reveals that genuine Christian freedom encompasses both practices when both are done "for the Lord" (vv6-8). The God who accepts both is not indifferent to practice but is concerned with the heart-orientation of the practice. Christ himself lived within the constraints of Jewish food law during his ministry (eating with tax collectors and sinners, but not violating kashrut); his freedom was expressed not in ignoring constraints but in serving love within and beyond them.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "The one who eats everything must not treat with contempt the one who does not, and the one who does not eat everything must not judge the one who does, for God has accepted them." The mutual welcome that God extends to both the strong and the weak — without demanding identical practice as the condition of acceptance — reveals the breadth of divine grace. God does not only accept those whose practice exactly matches the theological ideal; he accepts all who are "in Christ" (8:1). The community that judges each other\'s practices in areas where God has not made distinctions presumes to be a more demanding gatekeeper than God himself.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "Who are you to judge someone else\'s servant? To their own master, servants stand or fall." The Lordship of Christ over every believer — making each one Christ\'s servant, not the community\'s — is the revelation that relativizes the judgments members pass on one another. Christ is Lord; the believer is servant; the community is fellow-servant. The Judge before whom all will stand is not the community\'s opinion but Christ himself. This relativization of human judgment is liberating rather than anarchic: it establishes the space in which genuine diversity of practice can coexist within unity of Lord.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "Each of them should be fully convinced in their own mind" — the principle of conscience-directed practice reflects the divine respect for the person as a moral agent who is accountable to God for their own judgments. God did not create humanity as mechanical law-keepers but as image-bearers with moral capacity. The conscience-before-God (<em>syneidēsis</em>) is the internal representation of that divine-human accountability: the person who is "fully persuaded" (the same <em>pepeismai</em> of 4:21 — Abraham\'s full persuasion about the divine promise!) in their own conscience acts from faith rather than from external constraint.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "The one who regards the day, regards it for the Lord; the one who eats, eats for the Lord, giving thanks to God; the one who abstains, abstains for the Lord and gives thanks." The three-times-repeated "for the Lord" reveals that the divine goal for every practice — whether observing days or abstaining from foods — is the same: the Lord\'s honor and the worshiper\'s gratitude. The God who receives both the Sabbath-keeper\'s honor and the every-day-is-equal person\'s honor is the God who looks on the heart (1 Sam 16:7) and receives the offering when it is genuinely for him.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct revelation: "For none of us lives to himself and none dies to himself." The Lordship of Christ over life and death — which v8 makes explicit — is the revelation that eliminates self-referential existence as an option for the new covenant community. The community constituted by the one who "did not live to please himself" (15:3) cannot live self-referentially. The cross is the ultimate display of not-living-for-oneself: Christ\'s entire life and death were "for God" and "for us" simultaneously. The community that does not live for itself participates in the same orientation.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct revelation: "If we live, we live to the Lord; if we die, we die to the Lord. So, whether we live or die, we belong to the Lord." This is among the clearest statements of Christ\'s universal Lordship in Paul. The Lordship of Christ encompasses not merely religious life but all of life and death itself — the ultimate horizons of human existence. No domain falls outside this Lordship; no moment in life or in death is exempt from it. The believer who grasps this does not fear death (because to die is to die "to the Lord" = to pass into his more immediate presence) and does not cling to life (because life is also under his Lordship and can be given away in service).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct revelation: "For this very purpose Christ died and returned to life, so that he might be the Lord of both the dead and the living." This verse states the purpose of the death and resurrection most concisely in the entire letter: the cross and resurrection are the events by which Christ\'s universal Lordship was established over all times and all persons, living and dead. The resurrection of Christ is thus not merely a personal vindication or a sign of individual hope but a sovereignty-event — the moment when the Father installed the Son as Lord over death itself (1 Cor 15:25-26: "he must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet, the last enemy being death").</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "We will all stand before God\'s judgment seat." The eschatological tribunal before which every believer will give account discloses the divine justice that does not overlook any deed or attitude — including the judging-of-one-another that Paul has been addressing. The same God who accepts both strong and weak in Christ will also call all of them to account for how they treated each other. The judgment seat relativizes human tribunals (community opinion, theological gatekeeping) precisely because it is absolute: nothing escapes the divine scrutiny, and the standard is the Lord himself before whom all pretensions collapse.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A fulfillment: "It is written: As I live, says the Lord, every knee will bow before me; every tongue will acknowledge God" (Isa 45:23). This OT affirmation of YHWH\'s universal sovereignty is applied by Paul to Christ in Philippians 2:10-11 ("at the name of Jesus every knee shall bow... every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord"). The citation in Romans 14:11 grounds the eschatological tribunal in the divine sovereignty that Isaiah proclaimed over all nations. The God who will receive the universal acknowledgment of every creature is the God who gave his Son for those creatures — the judge is also the redeemer.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "Each of us will give an account of ourselves to God." The individual accountability before the divine judge is not a threat but a revelatory principle: each person is a moral agent, responsible for their own response to the Lord they serve. The God who holds each person individually accountable is the God who deals with persons as persons, not as masses or tribes. This individual accountability before God is also the basis of the community\'s freedom from judging one another: if God holds each person directly accountable, no human intermediary is necessary or welcome in that accounting.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "Let us stop judging one another. Instead make up your mind not to put any stumbling block or obstacle in the way of a brother or sister." The shift from condemning-the-other to evaluating-one\'s-own-impact-on-the-other reflects the God who considers the wellbeing of the other before asserting his own rights. Christ, who "had every right" to remain in the divine form but gave up that right for the sake of those who needed him (Phil 2:6-8), is the supreme model of this self-evaluating love. The strong Christian who evaluates their freedom\'s impact on the weak is following the one who "became weak for our sakes" (2 Cor 8:9).</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct revelation: "I know and am fully persuaded in the Lord Jesus that nothing is unclean in itself." This Christological grounding of the food-freedom — "in the Lord Jesus" — indicates that it is Christ\'s word and authority (Mark 7:19: "he declared all foods clean") that establishes the freedom. The revelation is not merely a new rule but a new framework: in Christ, the old clean/unclean distinctions that separated Jew from Gentile at the table have been abolished, not by human consensus but by divine action. The cross broke down the "dividing wall" (Eph 2:14) that included the food-law boundary.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: "If your brother or sister is distressed because of what you eat, you are no longer acting in love. Do not by your eating destroy someone for whom Christ died." The Christological intensifier — "for whom Christ died" — is the decisive revelation. The person whose conscience might be wounded is not merely a fellow church member but someone for whom the Son of God gave his life. This makes the casual exercise of freedom at the expense of another\'s conscience not merely impolite but a grave offense against the redemption-value of the person. Christ\'s death establishes the infinite worth of every believer; wounding them for the sake of food dismisses that value.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "Do not let what you consider good be spoken of as evil." The concern for the community\'s external reputation reflects the divine missionary purpose: the community exists not only for its members but as a witness to the watching world. God\'s purpose in election was never merely the salvation of the elect but the blessing of all nations through the elect (Gen 12:3). The community\'s internal conflicts, when they become the basis for outsiders speaking ill of the gospel, damage not just the community\'s reputation but God\'s mission in the world.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: "For the kingdom of God is not a matter of eating and drinking, but of righteousness, peace and joy in the Holy Spirit." This is Paul\'s most direct description of the kingdom\'s content — and it is entirely Christological and pneumatological. "Righteousness" (the right-standing before God established in Christ), "peace" (the shalom reconciliation accomplished by the cross, 5:1), and "joy in the Holy Spirit" (the Spirit\'s gift, Gal 5:22) are the substance of the kingdom that Christ established and that the Spirit communicates. Food and drink are penultimate matters; these three are ultimate and eternal.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "Anyone who serves Christ in this way is pleasing to God and receives human approval." The standard of divine approval — serving Christ by prioritizing righteousness, peace, and joy over food-rights — reveals what God values most: not correct dietary practice but the community relationships that reflect the kingdom\'s character. The God who is pleased by this service is the God who received Christ\'s service with the words: "This is my Son, whom I love; with him I am well pleased" (Matt 3:17). The community that serves Christ as Christ served the Father participates in the same Father-approval.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "Let us therefore make every effort to do what leads to peace and to mutual edification." The divine purpose for the community — shalom-building and mutual upbuilding — reflects God\'s own creative and redemptive purpose: to build a people (Eph 2:19-22: "you are being built together to become a dwelling in which God lives by his Spirit"). The God who is building the community through the Spirit uses the community\'s own efforts toward peace and edification as the materials of that construction. The active verbs ("make every effort," <em>diōkōmen</em>) indicate that this building-work requires human participation in the divine purpose.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "Do not tear down the work of God for the sake of food." The divine construction project (<em>to ergon tou theou</em> = the work of God, the community being built by God) is placed against the trivial cause of food-disputes. The God who is the divine builder (1 Cor 3:9: "you are God\'s building") does not demolish his own work; the community members who tear it down by insisting on food-rights work against the divine purpose. The seriousness of damaging the divine building project is proportional to the greatness of the builder — it is the work of the sovereign God that is at stake.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "It is better not to eat meat or drink wine or to do anything else that will cause your brother or sister to fall." The willingness to limit genuine freedom for the sake of another\'s wellbeing is the character of the God who "emptied himself" for our sake. God was "free" from any obligation to create, to redeem, to send his Son — yet he chose to limit his own freedom by the constraints of covenant love. Christ was "free" from the constraints of the incarnation — yet he chose to enter them for our sake. The community\'s voluntary limitation of freedom echoes the divine kenosis (self-emptying) that is the pattern of all genuine love.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "Blessed is the one who does not condemn himself by what he approves." The <em>makarios</em> (blessed) — the word of beatitude from Jesus\'s Sermon on the Mount and from Psalm 1 — is pronounced over the person whose conscience and action are integrated: who believes a practice is right and acts accordingly without violating conscience. The blessing is not over correct theology or correct practice alone but over the integration of inner conviction and outer action — the integrity that characterizes the God who is the same in his inner being and his outer expression (the Son is the exact image of the Father, Heb 1:3).</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "Everything that does not come from faith is sin." This is Paul\'s broadest ethical principle — and it is explicitly theological: faith (<em>pistis</em>) as the organizing center of the moral life means that the alignment of action with trust-in-God is the standard of righteousness. An action done in violation of conscience — even if externally permissible — is sinful because it is done in contradiction to the person\'s own faith-relationship with God. This makes the moral life relational rather than merely legal: sin is not merely breaking a rule but breaking faith, acting in ways inconsistent with one\'s relationship to the Lord. Christ\'s life was the perfect expression of faith-as-moral-center: every action was from faith, through love, toward the Father.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'romans')
    merge_comm(existing, ROMANS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'romans', existing)
    print('Romans 11–14 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
